  "description": [
    "sHi a cu i in nit OFFICHOIDING EDITOR N 0 Picayune The New York Nation a paper of mark ed ability and decided weight thinks that the Civil Service Commissioners would have added to the value of their works if they had when drawing up their rules formally disqualified all editors and pub lishers of newspapers as long as they remain editors and publishers from hold ing any office in the gift of the Govern ment It is thought that although such a rule would give marked offense to the press and cause a general denunciation of the civl service reform movement at the san e time the moral effect would be good when power of the press in office is con sidered There can be no doubt that an honest performance of the work and duties of journalism is incompatible with simulta neous office holding for the work will take its color from the office or a lively sense of official lavors toe me In the n ajority ot cases such is the weakness ol the aver age moral backbone The press to be the bulwark of liberty must remain free from and urtrammeled by the spoils of office"
